there is little evidence for a reconstructible consonant *b, but some widespread items (e.g. the suspected Wanderwort abaw ‘faba bean’) might still point to such a phoneme in Proto-Berber. If so, it still seems probable that this was a recent phenomenon at the moment that Berber started to diverge

The reconstruction of fricative realizations of β, f and ɣ is based on the evidence of attested Berber variants. In the case of *β a large group of Berber languages (but not Ghadames, Awjila and Zenaga) have a plosive realization of this phoneme in pre-consonantal position (except in cases of voice assimilation where *β > f). All Berber varieties have [f]. With the exception of two closely related languages (Zenaga and Tetserrét), *ɣ is always realized as a fricative. In Zenaga *ɣ > ʔ (thus merging with *ʔ), while it is lost in Tetserrét (like *ʔ). Some scholars (e.g. Souag) have suggested that this points to an ancient realization *[q]. For reasons concerning assimilations, I would rather reconstruct *[ɢ] as the pre-Zenaga realization.

The reconstruction of these sounds in Kossmann (1999) would have to be assessed again if one reconstructs a contrast *ĭ vs *ŭ (see below); note that they seem to have merged with (or failed to split from) *k and *g in pre-consonantal position.

This phoneme was reconstructed by Taine-Cheikh (2004) and Kossmann (2001) on the basis of Zenaga evidence. There is no comparative evidence for more than one glottal (or pharyngeal) sound in proto-Berber. Internal reconstructions by Prasse have shown that the reconstruction of a second glottal/pharyngeal sound would simplify parts of verbal and nominal morphology.
